<div id="review_3347602357" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3347602357" />
    <a title="Steve" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48011083-steve"><img alt="Steve" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1542289434p2/48011083.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3347602357?book_show_action=true">May 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve" href="/user/show/48011083-steve">Steve</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3347602357" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer189774698907715898"><i>Bonjour Tristesse</i> is an engaging novella. In rather short order, I found sharp contempt for Céline, the main character, a destructress and a reminder of our potential to inflict emotional cruelty amid betrayal, even to our closest family. I imagine a Sisyphean dilemma; by nature, we are communal, subject to a spectrum of miseries in our nearest relationships; yet the antidote, solitude, seems an impossible, unsustainable alternative.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


