    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_152430037" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/152430037" />
    <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly"><img alt="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349701607p2/2190636.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/152430037?book_show_action=true">Mar 06, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly">Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer152430037" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5098266943206121229">This caused a sensation when it was first published in 1959. Why? The author was just 18 years old when she wrote this and the principal protagonist was a 17-year-old girl, with her 40-year-old wealthy father, both carefree and hedonistic. The father treats his sexual conquests like sporting events; the daughter (who narrates the story), in turn, admits that her love of pleasure &quot;seems to be the only coherent side of (her) character.&quot; She&apos;s &quot;vaguely uncomfortable with anyone devoid of physical c</span>
  <span id="freeText5098266943206121229" style="display:none">This caused a sensation when it was first published in 1959. Why? The author was just 18 years old when she wrote this and the principal protagonist was a 17-year-old girl, with her 40-year-old wealthy father, both carefree and hedonistic. The father treats his sexual conquests like sporting events; the daughter (who narrates the story), in turn, admits that her love of pleasure "seems to be the only coherent side of (her) character." She's "vaguely uncomfortable with anyone devoid of physical charms" and the only thing she describes as somehow "indecent" (even with all her father's amorous escapades in full view), are those plain-looking people who are "resigned to the fact that they are unattractive."<br /><br />Think Paris Hilton (or maybe Lindsay Lohan?) with anyone of her parents. The famously rich surrounded by beauty. The only difference, perhaps, is that while Francoise Sagan's heroine (or Sagan herself) showed a lot of promise and literary sophistication at such a young age (the beach, she's sunbathing, her lover approaches her, she hears his voice, but she could not speak because, as she magnificently says, she "was nailed to the sand by all the forces of summer"), her modern day versions could hardly write one complete paragraph without being objects of derision.<br /><br />A nice little pocketbook of only about a hundred pages. Quite a disgusting accomplishment! Only wimps read cute little books like this! To regain my self-respect, I shall now face the ten demons in my closet, books in the 1001 list which I have not read and with more than 500 pages each:<br /><br />1. A TALE OF LOVE AND DARKNESS -Amos Oz, 517 pages;<br />2. LANARK: A LIFE IN FOUR BOOKS - Alasdair Gray, 573 pages;<br />3. THE COMPLETE STORIES OF SAKI - Hector Hugh Munro, 594 pages;<br />4. LOST ILLUSIONS - Honore de Balsac, 641 pages;<br />5. GREEN HENRY - Gottfried Keller, 706 pages;<br />6. THE FORSYTE SAGA - John Galsworthy, 715 pages;<br />7. IN THE FIRST CIRCLE - Alexandr Solzhenitsyn, 741 pages;<br />8. PARADE'S END - Ford Madox Ford, 836 pages;<br />9. BELLE DU SEIGNEUR - Albert Cohen, 974 pages; <br /><br />and Satan himself:<br /><br />10. AGAINST THE DAY - Thomas Pynchon, 1220 pages.<br /><br /> 7,517 pages. If I read 30 pages a day, I'll finish all these in about 8 months. Only then can I have a really merry christmas.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5098266943206121229" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review152430037">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
