    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2248772159" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2248772159" />
    <a title="Fede" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73964263-fede"><img alt="Fede" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626976231p2/73964263.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2248772159?book_show_action=true">Jan 07, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fede" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fede" href="/user/show/73964263-fede">Fede</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/73964263-fede?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/73964263-fede?shelf=french">french</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2248772159" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4229139368206012572">&quot;Mes jours comme mes nuits sont en tous points pareils, sans joies et pleins d&apos;ennui...&quot; <br/><br/>Françoise Hardy&apos;s words are quite fitting when it comes to describing the languorous atmosphere of &quot;Bonjour Tristesse&quot;, another Françoise&apos;s first novel. An important novel, in spite of its flaws and shortcomings: one of those books a whole society must cope with once in a decade. <br/><br/>F. Sagan is only eighteen when she writes about Cécile, seventeen, a pampered teenage Parisian living with a pampered young father</span>
  <span id="freeText4229139368206012572" style="display:none">"Mes jours comme mes nuits sont en tous points pareils, sans joies et pleins d'ennui..." <br /><br />Françoise Hardy's words are quite fitting when it comes to describing the languorous atmosphere of "Bonjour Tristesse", another Françoise's first novel. An important novel, in spite of its flaws and shortcomings: one of those books a whole society must cope with once in a decade. <br /><br />F. Sagan is only eighteen when she writes about Cécile, seventeen, a pampered teenage Parisian living with a pampered young father, Raymond. A life that so far has been pretty comfortable for both: wealthy, shallow, free; no pressure, no expectations; daddy's volatile relationships are a funny pastime in which Cécile is a willing accomplice. Until summer comes.<br /><br />A hot summer on the Côte d'Azur. The sea, the blinding sun, a house on the beach... then father and daughter are joined by Anne, an acquaintance from Paris, a woman whose charm and intelligence are definitely new to both of them. <br />The troubles begin when Raymond suddenly falls in love with Anne, who expects him to behave as a man and straighten up once and for all. The sight of her father utterly spellbound by the prospect of growing up horrifies Cécile, whose feelings for Anne are painfully in contrast with her frivolous attitude toward life. She's strangely attracted to this woman - an attraction that often gets almost physical - fascinated and bewildered by her uniqueness; at the same time she senses all the danger Anne represents, how radically she's going to change their life. Anne is not one of the cheerful morons her father picks up wantonly, forever in need to feel young and attractive; this woman is a threat to their life of ease and irresponsibility. <br />Naive and merciless, childish and cold blooded, what Cécile sets in motion is a cruel game in which everyone gets involved: Raymond, his ex girlfriend, Cécile summer boyfriend. Tragedy will inexorably seal the last summer of Cécile's innocence. <br /><br />Sagan is neither Yourcenar nor Beauvoir. She's not Duras... nor Arsan, if anything. She's a teenager who writes about another teenager, basically describing her own life and the adult world as she sees it: the glamourous milieu of wealthy post-war France. Hedonism has prevailed over any sort of intellectual or political commitment, let aside the leftist intelligentsia of the 50s and 60s - already turning into a caricature of itself when Sagan writes her novel. It's 1954: Algeria is getting out of control, the situation in Vietnam is falling apart, but nobody really cares as long as De Gaulle says it's all right. <br />Her being far from any intellectual commitment is precisely what makes her work so powerful and momentous. It takes a girl of 18 to talk about the sexual acts and thoughts of young people, a revelation that sounds more spontaneous and genuine when it doesn't come from an old lady remembering her pre-war high times (Duras) or a diplomat's wife bored to death (Arsan). <br />It's a modern counterpoint to "Les Liaisons Dangereuses". Same coldness, same ruthlessness in planning the destruction of other people's hopes and expectations. Cécile is a puppeteer, the deus ex machina of the game, until she realises that nobody - not even her - really knows how to play it. <br />"Bonjour Tristesse" (the title comes from a poem by Paul Éluard) is still a scandalous book. It's a book on cruelty: the cruelty of innocence and the innocence of cruelty. <br /><br />Sagan's talent burnt itself soon after the enormous success of her first novel. The unexpected celebrity, the greed of publishers and readers, the expectations, the attention of intellectuals and ideologues (not to mention drugs, alcohol, failed relationships, a major car crash...) destroyed her potential from the very beginning. <br />"Bonjour Tristesse" is the spiritual testament of a generation of wasted intelligence and talent, gone sour on a path of easy money and excess. <br />The Mediterranean waves of the Côte d'Azur echo with a sadness we don't really feel like greeting with a Bonjour. <br /><br />Bonjour à toi, Françoise... où que tu sois. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4229139368206012572" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


